Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I totally agree that this is how the API _should_ behave. However, it's a departure from how it _does_ behave today. People code to the APIs as they behave, not always as they are documented, and especially if they are not documented at all. The API WG guidelines cover this pretty clearly:

 “The existing API is not well documented.”

 If an API’s behavior isn’t adequately documented, then developers using the API have no choice but to
 go by what they observe the behavior to be. A change that will violate those observations is a change 
 that requires a version.

From https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/api-wg/guidelines/api_interoperability.html#interoperability in the examples section.

In this case, we would be breaking anyone that currently assumes that they are passing the eventual set of tags. Something that adds a tag and removes another by passing the full set would suddenly stop removing the tag they don't pass. If glance had microversion support, we could change this behavior in the new microversion and continue to honor the old behavior, but we don't.

So I think that the proper way to fix this (aside from adopting microversions, which we should!) is to add a new optional parameter indicating the intent, which defaults to the old behavior. Something like "?append=False" which can be overridden to "?append=True" to get the new behavior would be compatible. We could make glanceclient default to the new behavior, but the REST API itself would remain unchanged for people who don't opt-in to this new behavior.
